  • Since these data resulted from a random process, we can make generalizations using the data in hands. However, we should be careful to not extrapolate our results beyond the range of our data points (e.g. we should be very cautious when making predictions about movies released before 1970 or after 2014).

  • This data did not come out from experimental settings. Since no random assignment was used in generating these data, we cannot infer causality from our analysis; we can only state associations and correlations between different variables.

Part 2: Research question

My research question is: Which movies characteristics do have the highest influence on predicting ratings on IMDB website?

  • The answer of this question could benefit movie makers and guide them on their choices and movies production since a large section of movies consumers make their decisions of purchasing based on IMDB ratings.

  • To answer this question, I will build a multiple linear regression model. However, since we have 20 variables in our dataset, it would be a good idea if we first built some intuition about the relationship between predictor variables and response variables in the EDA section.

  • Our response variable is: imdb_rating for IMDB model and critics_score for Rotten Tomatoes.

  • Our potential predictors (also confounders or effect modifiers) are: title_type, genre, runtime, mpaa_rating, thtr_rel_year, dvd_rel_year, imdb_num_votes, audience_score, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, top200_box

From the plot above, we can notice that the dataset has a lot of movies of both comedy and drama genres in comparison with other types of movies. Also, the positive strong relationship is as well more pronounced in these two kinds of movies as well.

# Plot a correlation matrix
corrplot(cor(na.omit(movies[,c(4,7,8,9,10,12,14)])), method = "number", type = "full")

Among our seven numerical variables, imdb_rating is moderately to strongly associated with critics_score (r=0.76)(r=0.76) and audience_score (r=0.86)(r=0.86). There is also some correlation, though weak, between imdb_rating and both imdb_num_votes and runtime with correlation coefficients of (r=0.33)(r=0.33) and (r=0.27)(r=0.27), respectively.

Part 4: Modeling

IMDB ratings model

  • In this model, I will use imdb_ratings as a response variable.
  • From our EDA, we observed how some variables are not well correlated with imdb_ratings. Nonetheless, I will incorporate almose all of them in the model. I will exclude the names of the studios studio and the names of the movies title. Also, I will only add one Rotten Tomatoes parameter to avoid colinearity.
ImdbCrudeModel <- lm(data = movies, imdb_rating ~ title_type+ runtime + genre + mpaa_rating + thtr_rel_year + imdb_num_votes + critics_score + best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box,)

A. Selecting model based on p-value-based backward elimination:

  • Next, I followed step-wise backward elimination technique based on p-values of the coefficients.
  • The basic idea behind this method is to include all variables in hands into the model. Then, step by step, we remove the variable that has the highest p-value. Next, we re-run the model and repeat the same steps again until reaching a model whose all of its coefficients are statistically significant.
  • The best model is shown below:
p_imdb_model <- lm(data = movies, imdb_rating ~ runtime + genre  + imdb_num_votes + critics_score )

B. Selecting model based on adjusted R2R2 -based backward elimination:

  • Also, I used stepwise backward elimination but based on adjusted R-squared this time.
  • The basic idea behind this method is to include all variables in hands into the model. Then, step by step, we remove variables one by one and re-run to see what happens to the adjusted R2R2 value. We remove a variable from the model if its removal did no reduce or, in fact, increased the adjusted R2R2 value.
  • The best model is shown below:
Imdb_radjust <- lm(data = movies, imdb_rating ~  runtime + genre + thtr_rel_year + imdb_num_votes + critics_score + best_pic_win + top200_box)

4- Check for independence among observations:

Since each observation represents a different movies, there is reason to assume any kind of relationship among observations. Hence, we can say that observations are independent.

  • Our final model is as follows:

Interpretation of model coefficients

  • All other variables held constant, for each one additional minute in movies runtime, the IMDB rating is expected to go up, on average, by 0.004 on ratings scale out of 10.
  • All other variables held constant, documenary, art, drama, musical, and mystery movies have on average higher IMDB ratings when compared to action and adventures movies (reference value).
  • All other variables held constant, animcation, comdey, horror, science fiction movies and movies categorized as other have on average lower IMDB ratings when compared to action and adventures movies (reference value).
  • All other variables held constant, for each one additional point in Rotten Tomatoes critics_score ratings, the IMDB rating is expected to go up, on average, by 0.024 on ratings scale out of 10.
  • Else held constant, movies whose its producers won the best picture award have, on average, less IMDB ratings than those which lost the award by a difference of 0.279.
  • Else held constant, movies ranked among the top 200 in box office have, on average, less IMDB ratings than those not ranked in the list by a difference of 0.203.

Part 5: Prediction

  • I chose to see if my model can predict the score of the Deadpool movie.
  • Details and information used to build deadpool dataframe was taken from these links( 1 and 2)
# create the deadpool dataframe
deadpool <- data.frame(runtime = 108,
                       genre = "Comedy",
                       thtr_rel_year = 2016,
                       imdb_num_votes = 863132,
                       critics_score = 85,
                       top200_box = "yes",
                       best_pic_win = "no")

# Predict
predict(Imdb_radjust, newdata = deadpool, interval = "confidence")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 8.359492 7.878282 8.840702

From the code output, the model predicts that the movie will have a score of 8.36 with a confidence interval of 7.87 and 8.84. This is a really good prediction since the true IMDB rating 8.0/10, which lies in the interval given by the model.

Part 6: Conclusion

In our analysis, we managed to build a model that can help us to predict the IMDB ratings of different movies. Our out-of-sample prediction was successful in estimating the IMDB rating of a movie released in 2016. The main shortcoming in my opinion is that I dont have much experience in movies metrics. Therefore, a risk of colinearity could actually exist.
